ath9k_htc: ackmon — hardware-ACK a fixed BSSID set on a monitor vif

DRAFT / UNTESTED — build and validate on real AR9271 hardware.

Rationale
=========
The AR9271 PCU ACKs a received unicast frame when its RA matches the device
address under the BSSID mask:

    (RA & bssidmask) == (macaddr & bssidmask)

`macaddr` is propagated to the target as the monitor vif's `myaddr`
(AR_STA_ID); `bssidmask` is programmed by ath_hw_setbssidmask() (AR_BSSMSK).
Nothing in ath9k ever sets AR_DIAG_ACK_DIS, so ACK is *not* disabled in
monitor mode — it simply never fires because no frame is addressed to the
sniffer's MAC.

ackmon overrides macaddr=<base> and bssidmask=<mask> for a single monitor
vif so the chip hardware-ACKs every BSSID in the masked set, while the vif
still captures and injects raw. No AP/hostapd runs locally; the real APs
live on the vwifi medium and remain the literal APs. Only the SIFS ACK is
provided locally — Auth/Assoc/EAPOL are relayed to the VMs.

Use a dedicated lab adapter running ONLY a monitor vif. Choose prefix-aligned
BSSIDs so the mask is tight, e.g. base 02:11:22:33:44:00, mask ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:fc
covers 02:11:22:33:44:00..03.

Apply against drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath9k/htc_drv_main.c. Line numbers are
approximate; the two insertion points are (1) just after the module includes /
top-of-file statics, and (2) inside ath9k_htc_set_mac_bssid_mask(), immediately
before the ath_hw_setbssidmask(common) call.

---
--- a/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath9k/htc_drv_main.c
+++ b/drivers/net/wireless/ath/ath9k/htc_drv_main.c
@@ (top of file, after the existing #includes)
+/* ----------------------------------------------------------------------
+ * ackmon: hardware-ACK a configured BSSID set on a monitor vif (lab use).
+ * See ackmon/README.md in the qemu-vwifi tree.
+ * ---------------------------------------------------------------------- */
+static bool ackmon;
+module_param(ackmon, bool, 0644);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(ackmon, "ACK a fixed BSSID set on a monitor vif (lab use)");
+
+static char *ackmon_base = "02:11:22:33:44:00";
+module_param(ackmon_base, charp, 0644);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(ackmon_base, "ackmon: RA-match base MAC (the BSSID prefix)");
+
+static char *ackmon_mask = "ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:fc";
+module_param(ackmon_mask, charp, 0644);
+MODULE_PARM_DESC(ackmon_mask, "ackmon: address mask (1=care, 0=don't-care)");
+
@@ static void ath9k_htc_set_mac_bssid_mask(struct ath9k_htc_priv *priv,
 	memcpy(common->bssidmask, iter_data.mask, ETH_ALEN);

 	if (iter_data.hw_macaddr)
 		memcpy(common->macaddr, iter_data.hw_macaddr, ETH_ALEN);

+	if (ackmon) {
+		u8 base[ETH_ALEN], mask[ETH_ALEN];
+
+		if (!mac_pton(ackmon_base, base) || !mac_pton(ackmon_mask, mask)) {
+			ath_err(common,
+				"ackmon: bad base/mask MAC ('%s'/'%s')\n",
+				ackmon_base, ackmon_mask);
+		} else {
+			/*
+			 * The RA-match base becomes the device MAC; the mask
+			 * widens it so the PCU ACKs the whole BSSID set. The
+			 * monitor vif carries common->macaddr to the target as
+			 * hvif.myaddr, so AR_STA_ID follows automatically the
+			 * next time the monitor interface is (re)registered.
+			 */
+			memcpy(common->macaddr, base, ETH_ALEN);
+			memcpy(common->bssidmask, mask, ETH_ALEN);
+			ath_dbg(common, CONFIG,
+				"ackmon: macaddr=%pM bssidmask=%pM\n",
+				common->macaddr, common->bssidmask);
+		}
+	}
+
 	ath_hw_setbssidmask(common);
 }
---

Load + bring-up
===============
    sudo modprobe -r ath9k_htc
    sudo modprobe ath9k_htc ackmon=1 \
         ackmon_base=02:11:22:33:44:00 ackmon_mask=ff:ff:ff:ff:ff:fc

    sudo ip link set wlxc01c300da281 down
    sudo iw dev wlxc01c300da281 set type monitor
    sudo ip link set wlxc01c300da281 up           # monitor registered AFTER
    sudo iw dev wlxc01c300da281 set channel 6      # ackmon override is in place

Verify the override reached the chip:
    dmesg | grep ackmon          # macaddr/bssidmask line

Known-open items to confirm on hardware (the reason this is a DRAFT)
===================================================================
1. myaddr propagation: AR_STA_ID must end up = base. set_mac_bssid_mask runs
   on config/bss-info changes; confirm the monitor vif's myaddr is (re)sent to
   the target after the override. If not, toggle the monitor vif (down/up) once
   more after channel set, or move the override into the monitor-add path
   (__ath9k_htc_add_monitor_interface, where hvif.myaddr = common->macaddr).
2. The decisive risk: does the AR9271 firmware ACK in HTC_M_MONITOR opmode at
   all? Validate with the injection test in ackmon/README.md BEFORE relying on
   it. If the firmware suppresses monitor ACK regardless of AR_STA_ID, fall
   back to patching open-ath9k-htc-firmware.
3. This override is global while enabled — use a dedicated adapter with only a
   monitor vif up.
